WEBVTT

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:06.560
<v Teacher>What was again the word then for <i>it</i> or for <i>him</i> or for <i>you</i> (formal)?

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:07.200
<v Student><b>Lo.</b>

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:09.600
<v Teacher>If we make this feminine,

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:16.180
<v Teacher>so we change the <i>o</i> to an <i>a</i>, and we're going to see other examples of this way of making something feminine in Spanish,

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:19.220
<v Teacher>we get <b>la</b>. And this means <i>her</i>, <i>it</i>

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:20.920
<v Teacher>(a feminine thing),

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:22.600
<v Teacher>so objects as well.

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:24.200
<v Teacher>Well, not objects.

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:25.240
<v Teacher>Objects don't have gender.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:29.880
<v Teacher>When people speak about languages that have gender, they tend to think that the object has the gender.

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:31.880
<v Teacher>But it's not the object, it's the word.

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:35.960
<v Teacher>You might have two words for the same object, and one might be masculine and one might be feminine.

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:36.840
<v Teacher>So it's the word.

00:00:36.840 --> 00:00:40.440
<v Teacher>A feminine word for example usually are ones that end in <i>a</i>.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:41.960
<v Teacher>So like <b>casa</b>,

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:43.720
<v Teacher><i>house</i>.

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:45.559
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>I want to see it</i>,

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:48.740
<v Teacher>and with this <i>it</i> you mean the house.

00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:50.100
<v Teacher>What do you think you will say?

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:52.500
<v Teacher><i>I want to see it:</i>

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:54.260
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.640
<v Teacher>Now what else could that sentence mean, other than <i>I want to see it</i> (the feminine thing)?

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:01.320
<v Teacher>What else could it mean?

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:04.280
<v Student>Oh. It could also mean <i>I want to see her</i>.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:05.960
<v Teacher>Yes, exactly.

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:14.420
<v Teacher>So we get quite a few meanings just with this little <b>lo</b> and adding an <i>s</i> to it or changing the <i>o</i> to an <i>a</i>. We actually get a lot of options.

00:01:14.420 --> 00:01:20.260
<v Teacher><b>La</b> could mean <i>her</i>, and it also could mean <i>you</i> (formal) talking to a female.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:23.640
<v Teacher>So you could be saying <i>I want to see you</i>, formally.

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:29.560
<v Teacher>Now, where you use the formal language and the informal language really, really depends on the dialect.

00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:39.220
<v Teacher>So the safe way is to go in with the formal and to see what happens and to see how people address you and see how people address each other in this context, and you can adjust accordingly.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:50.720
<v Teacher>For example, in Spain, when you meet somebody, when you're going to a shop, when you meet somebody for the first time - with the exception of kind of young peers - the common thing is to begin speaking formally.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:58.660
<v Teacher>If I compare this to Buenos Aires, for example, in Argentina, it's almost never used, this formal way of addressing people.

00:01:58.660 --> 00:02:02.900
<v Teacher>In fact, it's used more often to insult somebody with an extra

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:10.360
<v Teacher>layer of sarcasm or irony, than say, than it's actually used sincerely to be formal.

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:11.640
<v Teacher>So it really depends on the place.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:16.120
<v Teacher>You want to go and see. But to play safe, you can use the formal, which will be <b>lo</b> or <b>la</b>,

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:21.760
<v Teacher>speaking to a male or to a female. <b>Lo</b> and <b>la</b> instead of <b>te</b>.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
<v Teacher><b>Quiere</b> means <i>he wants</i>, <i>she wants</i>,

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:29.180
<v Teacher><i>it wants</i> or <i>you</i> (formal) <i>want</i>.

00:02:29.180 --> 00:02:34.780
<v Teacher>We can see that these four, they band together. Not just in words like <b>lo</b> and <b>la</b>, but in the verbs as well.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:35.740
<v Teacher>We saw it with <b>es</b>,

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:40.780
<v Teacher>that <b>es</b> means <i>it is</i>, <i>she is</i>, <i>he is</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>are</i>.

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:42.379
<v Teacher>So they will band together.

00:02:42.379 --> 00:02:47.260
<v Teacher><b>Quiere</b> means <i>he wants</i>, <i>she wants</i>, <i>it wants</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>want</i>.

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:52.400
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>you want to visit me</i>?

00:02:53.020 --> 00:02:55.140
<v Student><b>Quiere visitarme.</b>

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:56.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:02:59.140
<v Teacher><b>Quiere visitarme.</b> <i>You want to visit me</i>.

00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:03.220
<v Teacher>Now if you want to make that a question, in English, you put <i>do</i>,

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:07.280
<v Teacher><i>do you want</i>? But in Spanish, you won't do anything like that.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:11.600
<v Teacher>In Spanish, you will just make it sound like a question with your voice.

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:15.200
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>Do you want to visit me?:</i>

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:17.379
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:18.819 --> 00:03:21.780
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>You don't want to visit me</i>?

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:24.620
<v Student><b>No quiere visitarme.</b>

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:26.860
<v Teacher>Well you sounded very sad when you said that.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:35.180
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say <i>Don't you want to visit me</i>? Again, English gets really complicated there. But not Spanish.

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:39.060
<v Teacher>So, <i>don't you want to visit me?:</i>

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:40.659
<v Student><b>¿No quiere visitarme?</b>

00:03:40.659 --> 00:03:41.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:42.340
<v Teacher><b>¿No quiere visitarme?</b>

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:44.200
<v Teacher>You could add the word for <i>why</i>.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:46.200
<v Teacher>The word for <i>why</i> is <b>por qué</b>.

00:03:46.200 --> 00:03:47.000
<v Teacher><b>Por qué.</b>

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:47.880
<v Student><b>Por qué.</b>

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:50.360
<v Teacher>It's actually the word for <i>because</i> as well.

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:53.960
<v Teacher>So <i>why don't you want to visit me?:</i>

00:03:58.160 --> 00:03:58.640
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:05.600
<v Teacher>The verb for <i>to come</i> is <b>venir</b>.

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:06.300
<v Student><b>Venir.</b>

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:10.940
<v Teacher>So of course you could hear /v/, like I just pronounced for you, so you would get the spelling <b>venir</b>.

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:14.860
<v Teacher>But more commonly you would hear /benir/, /benir/, like a soft <i>b</i>.

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:18.220
<v Teacher>Firstly, let's say, <i>do you want to come?:</i>

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:20.139
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:20.220 --> 00:04:21.500
<v Teacher><b>¿Quiere venir?</b>

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:27.580
<v Teacher>And a nice way to remember <b>venir</b>, actually, is <b>conveniente</b>, <i>convenient</i>, "with coming",

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:28.880
<v Teacher>when things come together.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:37.040
<v Teacher>Or if you ever heard <i>welcome</i> in Spanish, you might have heard <b>bienvenido</b> or <b>bienvenida</b>, <b>bienvenidos</b>, <b>bienvenidas</b>.

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:44.920
<v Teacher>Literally the same as <i>welcome</i>. <i>Well</i> is <b>bien</b>, and <i>come</i>, there we have <b>venidos</b>, a different version of <b>venir</b>.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:46.680
<v Teacher>So <b>venir</b>, <i>to come</i>.

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:49.960
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>the house</i>, it's <b>la casa</b>.

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:51.640
<v Student><b>La casa.</b>

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.640
<v Teacher>What was <i>to</i>?

00:04:53.880 --> 00:04:54.520
<v Student><b>A.</b>

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:56.360
<v Teacher>What is <i>to the house</i>?

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:57.800
<v Student><b>A la casa.</b>

00:04:57.800 --> 00:04:58.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:01.480
<v Teacher><i>Do you want to come to the house?:</i>

00:05:05.379 --> 00:05:05.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:09.300
<v Teacher>How'd you say <i>Do you want to come to visit me?</i>

00:05:09.300 --> 00:05:11.860
<v Teacher><i>Do you want to come to visit me?:</i>

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:17.400
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:19.880
<v Teacher><i>Don't you want to come to visit me?:</i>

00:05:25.860 --> 00:05:29.540
<v Teacher>Good. <b>¿No quiere venir a visitarme?</b>

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:31.580
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>why</i>?

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:32.700
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:35.820
<v Teacher><i>Why don't you want to come to visit me?:</i>

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:42.620
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:48.720
<v Teacher><b>¿Por qué no quiere venir a visitarme?</b> Good.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:52.960
<v Teacher>And of course, here we're using <b>a</b> because we have <b>venir</b>.

00:05:52.639 --> 00:06:01.840
<v Teacher>A verb of coming and going, like <b>voy</b>, <b>voy a</b>, <b>venir a</b>, when we're connecting to a "to" form.

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:11.680
<v Teacher>The word for <i>I owe</i>, <i>I owe</i> in Spanish is <b>debo</b>. <b>Debo.</b>

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:14.000
<v Student><b>Debo.</b>

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:14.800
<v Teacher><b>Debo.</b>

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:22.880
<v Teacher>The English word <i>debt</i> which is spelled <i>d-e-b-t</i> has this <i>b</i> from <b>debo</b>.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:23.560
<v Teacher>It comes from there.

00:06:23.560 --> 00:06:25.720
<v Teacher>We don't pronounce it in English, of course.

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:28.360
<v Teacher>But this word is from Latin

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.280
<v Teacher>and <b>debo</b> is <i>I owe</i>.

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:34.680
<v Teacher>The useful thing about <i>I owe</i> is that you can use it like <i>I must</i>.

00:06:34.539 --> 00:06:40.539
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I must continue</i>, you say <i>I owe to continue</i>.

00:06:40.539 --> 00:06:41.900
<v Teacher><i>I owe to continue</i>.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.819
<v Teacher>And that's the meaning of <i>I must continue</i>.

00:06:43.819 --> 00:06:44.860
<v Teacher>So how would you say that:

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:46.139
<v Teacher><i>I must continue</i>?

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:49.140
<v Student><b>Debo continuar.</b>

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:49.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:53.060
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I must identify it</i>?

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:56.440
<v Student><b>Debo</b>- <i>identify</i>. <i>Identification</i>.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:06:57.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:58.440
<v Student><b>Identificación.</b>

00:06:58.440 --> 00:06:59.040
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.440
<v Student><b>Identificar.</b>

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:01.040
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:04.139
<v Student>So it's <b>debo identificarlo</b>.

00:07:10.139 --> 00:07:10.699
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:10.699 --> 00:07:12.940
<v Teacher><b>Debo identificarlo.</b>

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:17.020
<v Teacher><i>I must</i> or <i>I owe to identify them</i>.

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:18.940
<v Teacher><i>I must identify them:</i>

00:07:19.540 --> 00:07:22.419
<v Student><b>Debo identificarlos.</b>

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:28.500
<v Teacher>Or if they were feminine things, what change do you think you would see?

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:29.220
<v Student><b>Las.</b>

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:29.700
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:31.500
<v Student><b>Debo identificarlas.</b>

00:07:31.500 --> 00:07:32.000
<v Teacher>Good.
